We are enhancing the awareness of redundancy, and how much space we have pre-failure leaving us options for migration of data to other disks, should a disk fail. Prices of disks are rising, so this plugin aims to aid users in understanding that they still have space left to move data in the event of a disk failure.

These thresholds can be set to make clear to the user at first glance on the main page, that they are still safe, even after a disk failure to move data around and not have to worry about replacing the disks right away.

<b>All BTRFS RAID Profiles (mixed sizes supported!)</b><br>
BTRFS allocates in chunks and handles mixed disk sizes very well. See your RAID calculator sheet for how speeds are calculated based on base single-disk numbers per RAID type (e.g. for these drives ~540/550 MB/s 4TB, ~520/540 8TB):<br>
• <b>Single</b>: No redundancy. 100% space. Any failure = data loss.<br>
• <b>RAID 0</b>: Striping only. Max speed/space. No redundancy.<br>
• <b>RAID 1</b>: 2 copies on different devices. ~50% usable. Tolerates 1 failure.<br>
• <b>RAID 1c3</b>: 3 copies. ~33% usable. Tolerates 2 failures.<br>
• <b>RAID 1c4</b>: 4 copies. ~25% usable. Tolerates 3 failures.<br>
• <b>RAID 10</b>: Striped mirrors. ~50% usable. Good perf. Tolerates multiple failures (layout dependent).<br>
• <b>RAID 5</b>: Striping + 1 parity. ~(N-1)/N usable. Tolerates 1 failure.<br>
• <b>RAID 6</b>: Striping + 2 parity. ~(N-2)/N usable. Tolerates 2 failures.<br><br>

<b>Speed calculation method (per your sheet)</b><br>
Base single disk speeds (read/write) are measured, then for each RAID type the pool max is calculated as:<br>
- RAID0: sum of all individual read/write speeds<br>
- RAID1: read up to sum, write = single slowest<br>
- RAID10: read sum, write ~2x single (for mirrors)<br>
- RAID5: read sum, write ~(N-1) x single (parity)<br>
- etc. (see sheet for exact formula used for this drive set)<br><br>

<b>Speed calculation (per your sheet's method)</b><br>
Base single-disk speeds, then scaled per RAID (full sum for RAID0, limited for others).<br><br>

<b>Speed examples for this pool (based on sheet's base calc method for these drives):</b><br>
- RAID 0: ~2,080 MB/s read, ~2,160 write<br>
- RAID 1: ~2,080 read, ~540 write<br>
- RAID 5: ~2,080 read, ~820 write<br>
- RAID 6: ~2,080 read, ~547 write<br>
- RAID 1c3: ~2,080 read, ~540 write<br>
- RAID 1c4: ~2,080 read, ~540 write<br>
- RAID 10: ~2,080 read, ~1,080 write<br><br>

<b>What happens when a disk fails</b><br>
Pool goes degraded but stays usable. Reads come from remaining copies/parity. Writes lose redundancy until fixed.<br>
Recovery steps: replace the disk → <code>btrfs replace</code> or <code>btrfs device delete missing</code> + rebalance.<br>
Or temporarily convert to a lower-redundancy profile to free space, then convert back.<br>
Rebalance (<code>btrfs balance start -f /mnt/<?=htmlspecialchars($p)?></code>) moves chunks — it needs free space roughly equal to the data that was on the failed drive.<br><br>

<b>View in Unraid</b><br>
Go to <b>Main</b> tab → click the pool name → scroll to the <b>Balance Status</b> section.<br>
Direct link: <a href="/Main/Device?name=<?=urlencode($p)?>" target="_blank">/Main/Device?name=<?=htmlspecialchars($p)?></a><br><br>

<b>Example: 4×4 TB + 2×8 TB (32 TB raw)</b><br>
Possible profiles & usable space (approximate):<br>
• RAID0: 32 TB (no safety)<br>
• RAID1: ~16 TB (1 failure tolerance)<br>
• RAID10: ~16 TB (good perf)<br>
• RAID5: ~28 TB (1 failure, excellent space)<br>
• RAID6: ~24 TB (2 failures)<br><br>

<b>If you lose a 4 TB drive in RAID10</b><br>
Stripes that used it become single-copy. Performance drops. You can keep using the pool. To rebalance and restore full redundancy you typically need ~4 TB free (the volume of data that was on the failed drive needs new copies). <strong>Recommendation:</strong> Warning ≈ 8 T, Critical ≈ 4–5 T.<br><br>

<b>If you lose an 8 TB drive</b><br>
Larger device usually held more chunks → bigger rebalance requirement (often 6–8 TB free recommended). <strong>Recommendation:</strong> Warning 10–12 T, Critical 6–8 T.<br><br>

<b>Converting profiles (e.g. RAID10 → RAID5)</b><br>
RAID10 ~16 TB usable → RAID5 ~28 TB usable = you gain ~12 TB!<br>
Trade-off: you go from tolerating multiple failures to only 1.<br>
Rebalance to convert requires substantial free space (plan for 8–12+ TB during the operation).<br>
Performance: RAID5/6 has write parity overhead (slower small random writes). RAID10 is often snappier for mixed workloads. Reads are usually fine on both.<br><br>

<b>Our recommendations as the plugin</b><br>
Set your thresholds so the Main tab coloring already tells you that you are still safe to move data around and rebalance even after a disk failure—without having to replace disks right away.<br><br>

More advanced BTRFS guidance and dynamic per-pool suggestions are planned.
</blockquote>
